On June the 16th a Bombardier Q400 from Flybe started moving, on its own, over the ramp in Aberdeen airport. Several ramp- personnel tried to stop the aircraft using muscle power before they eventually gave up. The aircraft continued to roll across the tarmac and crashed into a parked Embraer ERJ 145 at stand 11.
No people were hurt in the incident but both aircraft were damaged. 
How can something like this happen and what can we learn from it?

How do you land an aircraft that has suffered dual engine failure, just after departure? Is it possible to glide an Airliner and what do you need to think about? 
This video was made a year ago but has become much more relevant after the PIA 8303 Crash in Pakistan last week. 
The first part of the video show the whole exercise uninterrupted, in the second part you will get the explanations. 
Make sure you watch the whole video to get everything explained in the second part, it will go very fast! 😊

Why are jet engines fitted outside the wings and not embedded inside? In what way are they actually attached and what could cause them to detach from the wings?
In todays episode I will be discussing all of these questions and a few more. We will be talking about shear-pins, bolts and thrust links. I will also present two case-studies at the end where the system didn't work as it was supposed to.
If you have more questions on this, or any other aviation topic, let me know in the comments below. I love answering your questions!

On the 19th of May a Swift Air Boeing 737-800 landed in San Diego, USA with a section of its tail missing. The aircraft was 21 years old when the incident occurred and it had been flying from Victorvill
The missing bit is referred to as a Dorsal fin and in this video I will be briefily explaining the purpose of that part as well as possible causes and how dangerous this would have been to the crew onboard.

The role of communication on the flight-deck cannot be overstated. Generally when you communicate with a person you are facing them so that you both can share facial expressions and body language but that’s NOT possible in a flight-deck.
This is why standard phraseology and very strict procedures are used but that’s ALSO why you need to use a good quality headset, especially when you are starting your training. 
You need to catch every little syllable of what your colleague or ATC is saying in order for the communication to flow as frictionless as possible in the beginning.

Have an awesome day my friends!
